    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1029891748" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1029891748" />
    <a title="Zanna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22591633-zanna"><img alt="Zanna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1512813535p2/22591633.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1029891748?book_show_action=true">Aug 18, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Zanna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Zanna" href="/user/show/22591633-zanna">Zanna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781590173022" href="/book/show/6145869-season-of-migration-to-the-north">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22591633-zanna?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22591633-zanna?shelf=g-african-reads">g-african-reads</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1029891748" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13683405630287110517">Laila Lalami reveals in the introduction to this slender volume that Tayeb Salih wrote in Arabic as a matter of principle, as <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/51936.Ng_g__wa_Thiong_o' title='Ngũgĩ wa Thiong’o' rel='nofollow noopener'>Ngũgĩ wa Thiong’o</a> decided to write in Gikuyu, explaining his decision in <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/152622.Decolonising_the_Mind_The_Politics_of_Language_in_African_Literature' title='Decolonising the Mind The Politics of Language in African Literature by Ngũgĩ wa Thiong’o' rel='nofollow noopener'>Decolonising the Mind: The Politics of Language in African Literature</a> with force and clarity: English is the language of colonisation, it cuts off the native from her culture, her people, enforces a way of knowing, a mode of relation and experience. Understanding this, I treasure the art of translati</span>
  <span id="freeText13683405630287110517" style="display:none">Laila Lalami reveals in the introduction to this slender volume that Tayeb Salih wrote in Arabic as a matter of principle, as <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/51936.Ng_g__wa_Thiong_o" title="Ngũgĩ wa Thiong’o" rel="nofollow noopener">Ngũgĩ wa Thiong’o</a> decided to write in Gikuyu, explaining his decision in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/152622.Decolonising_the_Mind_The_Politics_of_Language_in_African_Literature" title="Decolonising the Mind The Politics of Language in African Literature by Ngũgĩ wa Thiong’o" rel="nofollow noopener">Decolonising the Mind: The Politics of Language in African Literature</a> with force and clarity: English is the language of colonisation, it cuts off the native from her culture, her people, enforces a way of knowing, a mode of relation and experience. Understanding this, I treasure the art of translation that allows me, a monolingual reader, to commune with minds and worlds across the rivers of word. Lalami goes on to lament that there is very little Arabic literature well-translated into English. Last year I was privileged to read two books by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/1424397.Radwa_Ashour" title="Radwa Ashour" rel="nofollow noopener">Radwa Ashour</a>, so I know my problems with this book had nothing to do with its original language or translation.<br /><br />The theme of language did appeal to me. When the protagonist notes that the object of his fascination, Mustafa Sa'eed, had 'not a single Arabic book' in his collection, I understand that the disease of colonisation (which is identified as entering British people at the time of the Roman invasion) is carried by the word. I couldn't help noticing that the woman sitting next to me on the tube while I was reading this was reading a books called 'Life in the UK: a Guide for New Residents, intended as a study guide for the 'Life in the UK' residency/citizenship test, and the chapter she was on was called 'A Long and Illustrious History', a title which needs no comment. Still, I found faith that no immigrant could actually believe that fat, glossy, expensive book of propaganda. That the colonised subject, the racialised-as-other person, is awake and thinking, is well able to turn the coloniser's ignorance against her, is an idea taken up by Salih. Mustafa uses the language of Orientalist exotification to stoke the fantasies of women, so that he can have sexual affairs with them.<br /><br />My problems started more or less here. I appreciate that the people Mustafa is able to 'prey' on are those whose power is circumscribed (women). However, the text increasingly becomes an unpleasant male fantasy unable to give the women voice and intent. Mustafa collaborates with the women in exotifying him, but they are seen as victims. This could be read as a matter of viewpoint, but the narrative concurs with Mustafa's violent, dominating scheme, by killing the women off. His most intense relationship seems to be an entanglement of two psychopathic* personalities, which traumatises him and is fatal to her.<br /><br />(this paragraph is a bit spoilery but I recommend reading it anyway haha)<br />In the protagonist's native village Mustafa's influence causes havoc in his absence, as his former wife, Hosna, forced into a second marriage, defends herself against marital rape. I must own my standpoint here as a White British feminist, but I believe I speak with Black and Brown feminists &amp; allies of all faiths &amp; none when I assert that the bottom line is that no means no. So what am I to make of the brutal punishment the narrative metes out to Hosna? At least one woman stands with her in solidarity, but this character takes no previous or subsequent role in the text. The only other interesting female character, Bint Majzoub, who behaves 'like a man' takes a leading role in enforcing the patriarchal order. It is as if the disease of colonialism rather than native spirit, conviction or self-esteem caused Hosna to stand up for herself and destroyed her and others. There is no hope. The protagonist's final decision seems meaningless after this climax.<br /><br />I like unconventional narrative structures, and Salih's use of the story-within-a-story agreeably recalled, say, the Thousand and One Nights (which is repeatedly referenced). When Mustafa narrates, he constantly uses an 'exotic' image of himself as a desert nomad on the move 'saddling my camel' and so on, helping to orient(!) me in the slippery story as the protagonist slides into Mustafa's and his own memories frequently. This time-play was enjoyable, but as well as bridling at all the denouments, I was irritated by Mustafa's style, and the repetitious imagery wasn't to my taste. The book it most recalled to me was <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45967.The_Blind_Owl" title="The Blind Owl by Sadegh Hedayat" rel="nofollow noopener">The Blind Owl</a>, another classic which I strongly disliked for its poetic style.<br /><br />My favourite scene, the spontaneous party in the desert, combined a euphoric sense of instant community, the kind of thing that (almost) <a href="https://roseannastar.wordpress.com/2013/09/01/one-person-is-a-fiction-2/" rel="nofollow noopener">happens when you go to the theatre</a>, with a dreamlike ghostliness – the atmosphere that makes the classic cartoon <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HHCZhUZXhZU" rel="nofollow noopener">'The Snowman'</a> so haunting. The most enjoyable thing about this novel for me was the evocation of life along the Nile, the river and the desert and the lively life of the village, which the protagonist recognises and reveres in the person of his friend Mahjoub. In so far as Mahjoub embodies this vision, it is also attacked by the colonial disease that infects the protagonist; what I learn to love is threatened, but I will not accept that all is lost.<br /><br />Antidote: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10335337.Mr__Fox" title="Mr. Fox by Helen Oyeyemi" rel="nofollow noopener">Mr. Fox</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/80808.Helen_Oyeyemi" title="Helen Oyeyemi" rel="nofollow noopener">Helen Oyeyemi</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="13683405630287110517" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


