    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_981353760" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/981353760" />
    <a title="Nabse Bamato" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30631601-nabse-bamato"><img alt="Nabse Bamato" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442973857p2/30631601.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/981353760?book_show_action=true">Jun 29, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nabse Bamato" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nabse Bamato" href="/user/show/30631601-nabse-bamato">Nabse Bamato</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30631601-nabse-bamato?shelf=africa">africa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30631601-nabse-bamato?shelf=east-africa">east-africa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30631601-nabse-bamato?shelf=diaspora-challenge">diaspora-challenge</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30631601-nabse-bamato?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30631601-nabse-bamato?shelf=round-the-world-52-only-one-from-e">round-the-world-52-only-one-from-e</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer981353760" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16359968427705940253">It is easy to see why Season of Migration to the North has become recognised as a classic. Much better minds than mine, who are eminently qualified to comment on the novel have dissected it and analysed it and I would not wish to try and add to the discussion – it is more than is possible in a short review. However, I can tell you what I liked about it, and, as the 5 star rating shows, I did like it a lot. <br/><br/>The basic story is simple; a young (north) Sudanese man, who spent 7 years in Europe - and</span>
  <span id="freeText16359968427705940253" style="display:none">It is easy to see why Season of Migration to the North has become recognised as a classic. Much better minds than mine, who are eminently qualified to comment on the novel have dissected it and analysed it and I would not wish to try and add to the discussion – it is more than is possible in a short review. However, I can tell you what I liked about it, and, as the 5 star rating shows, I did like it a lot. <br /><br />The basic story is simple; a young (north) Sudanese man, who spent 7 years in Europe - and subsequently ends up working in Khartoum - returns to his village to find a new resident, Mustafa Sae’ed, living there. He is fascinated by this man, whose life story bears no small resemblance to his own, and attempts to discover more about Mustafa’s past. Their lives become strongly linked and by the end of the novel, circumstances bind them inextricably together. The writing style is, loosely, stream of consciousness (helping to tie the two stories together) and is beautifully evocative in its descriptions and imagery. Maybe it’s my background as an African (although not Sudanese) living in Europe but so much of the description feels familiar and the places throughout the story feel completely real. I can see them as I am reading.<br /><br />It seems to me essentially to be a novel about change. It is no accident that the village is located at a point where the Nile alters its direction. And, remembering that it was written in the 1960s , it is interesting to reflect how familiar some of the issues it addresses still feel. <br /><br />The back page of the edition I read describes it as “a powerful and evocative examination of colonization in two vastly different worlds.” This is doubtless true; there are numerous passages discussing various aspects of colonisation from a variety of viewpoints. In particular, the relative values of the traditional ways of making decisions via local committees are contrasted with civil service and working within the British system adopted in Khartoum. And the impact of colonisation is discussed from many different viewpoints, by both major and minor characters.<br /><br />However, in addition to that, the novel is an exploration of relationships between men and women during the sexual revolution of the 1960s in Europe. Women are significantly downtrodden throughout the story (in fact the whole novel starts by being addressed to “gentlemen”) and, interestingly, the one strong female character in the novel is from the village at the bend of the Nile (although arguably her strength comes from her behaving like a man). The discussions are complicated by an examination of European women’s relationships with African men (women do not come out of this well!) and this is contrasted with the relationships between men and women back in the village in Sudan. As I said, there is much to discuss and it would need several readings for me even to get close to forming a coherent thesis.<br /><br />However, as well as being an intellectual discussion of key issues in the 1960s, this is a beautifully written novel (hats off too to the translator). I would like to finish with a wonderful passage from the very first 2 pages, just to give a flavour of the writing. This is after the narrator returns to the village after being away for seven years studying in Europe, and has just woken up from his first night’s sleep in the bedroom of his childhood.<br /><br />“I listened intently to the wind: that indeed was a sound well known to me, a sound which in our village possessed a merry whispering – the sound of the wind passing through palm trees is different from when it passes through fields of corn. I heard the cooing of the turtle-dove and I looked through the window at the palm tree standing in the courtyard of our house and I knew that all was still well with life. I looked at its strong straight trunk, at its roots that strike down into the ground, at the green branches hanging down loosely over its top, and I experienced a feeling of assurance. I felt not like a storm-swept feather but like that palm tree, a being with a background, with roots, with a purpose.”<br /><br />Magical.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16359968427705940253" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


