    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1659429361" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1659429361" />
    <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera"><img alt="Inderjit Sanghera" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1564826235p2/900800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1659429361?book_show_action=true">Jun 05, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Inderjit Sanghera" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera">Inderjit Sanghera</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1659429361" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1006229796571931967">‘Season of Migration to the North’ is the story of a prodigiously talented and intelligent young Sudanese man, Mustafa Sa’eed, and his life in post-war England. The novel is replete with intensely poetic passages and beautiful metaphors-think of it as being like a modern day Arabian Nights, which explores post-colonial identity and the cult of orientalism; in many ways, Mustafa, cruel, capricious, exotic and lascivious, symbolises all this fetishisation of the ‘Orient’ by the West-Mustafa perpet</span>
  <span id="freeText1006229796571931967" style="display:none">‘Season of Migration to the North’ is the story of a prodigiously talented and intelligent young Sudanese man, Mustafa Sa’eed, and his life in post-war England. The novel is replete with intensely poetic passages and beautiful metaphors-think of it as being like a modern day Arabian Nights, which explores post-colonial identity and the cult of orientalism; in many ways, Mustafa, cruel, capricious, exotic and lascivious, symbolises all this fetishisation of the ‘Orient’ by the West-Mustafa perpetuates and plays upon this, but gradually loses his sense of self beneath the myriad of masks and disguises which he weaves about himself, until he ceases to become a man, but more an ideal, a symbol of Eastern decadence, of its savagery and seduction-the story is in many ways an analogy of the colonial mindset and he West’s attempt to ‘civilize’ the barbarism of the East. Mustafa is, however, not a particularly sympathetic character-not because of his seemingly endless string of seductions-although the story does seem to descend into the lowest realms of men’s fantasies at points, but more because of his callous indifference to those around him, to the women he seduces and the sense of cynicism he exudes. This is, of course, partially reflective of the fact that Mustafa is presented to us via the eyes of the narrator, whose grasp of reality can at times be tenuous and who creates an image of Mustafa in the same way that many of the English characters did. The novel is by no means perfect, some of the descriptions of Mustafa’s relationships with English women can become juvenile, and in the case of his relationship with Jean Morris, verging on the ridiculous, but is redeemed by the poetry of the prose style and power of the story. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1006229796571931967" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

