    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1488607057" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1488607057" />
    <a title="Bloodorange" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23066833-bloodorange"><img alt="Bloodorange" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1386872100p2/23066833.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1488607057?book_show_action=true">Jan 01, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bloodorange" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bloodorange" href="/user/show/23066833-bloodorange">Bloodorange</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9788362122042" href="/book/show/13081145-sezon-migracji-na-p-noc">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23066833-bloodorange?shelf=library">library</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/23066833-bloodorange?shelf=africa">africa</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1488607057" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13052944344141927741">Oh. Lord. How does one review a book which culminates in <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[three highly symbolic and parallel deaths <a class='jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction'>(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> and <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[an attempt at suicide, which symbolizes character’s rebirth <a class='jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction'>(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>?<br/><br/>My experience with <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/669780.Season_of_Migration_to_the_North' title='Season of Migration to the North by Tayeb Salih' rel='nofollow noopener'>Season of Migration to the North</a> was somewhat similar to reading <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/232937._The_Time_of_the_Doves__By_Rodoreda__Merce__Author__Paperback_on_01_Oct_1986' title='(The Time of the Doves) By Rodoreda, Merce (Author) Paperback on 01-Oct-1986 by Mercè Rodoreda' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Time of the Doves</a>, which – just like this book – is hailed the best book of the twentieth century written in its language: I approached both with expectations which weren’t met. I feel, h</span>
  <span id="freeText13052944344141927741" style="display:none">Oh. Lord. How does one review a book which culminates in <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[three highly symbolic and parallel deaths <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> and <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[an attempt at suicide, which symbolizes character’s rebirth <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>?<br /><br />My experience with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/669780.Season_of_Migration_to_the_North" title="Season of Migration to the North by Tayeb Salih" rel="nofollow noopener">Season of Migration to the North</a> was somewhat similar to reading <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/232937._The_Time_of_the_Doves__By_Rodoreda__Merce__Author__Paperback_on_01_Oct_1986" title="(The Time of the Doves) By Rodoreda, Merce (Author) Paperback on 01-Oct-1986 by Mercè Rodoreda" rel="nofollow noopener">The Time of the Doves</a>, which – just like this book – is hailed the best book of the twentieth century written in its language: I approached both with expectations which weren’t met. I feel, however, that I must give <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/669780.Season_of_Migration_to_the_North" title="Season of Migration to the North by Tayeb Salih" rel="nofollow noopener">Season of Migration to the North</a> the benefit of the doubt: whenever I read a book from outside my cultural circle, and consider its narrative construction to be less than effective, I fear I’m missing some references I would have probably known if I were more familiar with the given writing tradition/ period/ culture. The two storylines the book contains - Mustafa's and our unnamed narrator's – are very different and very differently handled, structure- and style-wise, but the narrative voice is compelling.<br /><br />I think the ending (referenced under the second spoiler alert of this review) is the pointer as to what happened to the protagonist, Mustafa. After I shook the inevitable associations with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/929782.Martin_Eden" title="Martin Eden by Jack London" rel="nofollow noopener">Martin Eden</a>, I understood it was about Mustafa, not the unnamed narrator. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Mustafa either stages this suicide, or actually wants to die (hence the letter and leaving his wife and sons in the narrator’s care), but changes his mind, similarly to the narrator.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> Waiting for the Bluebeard chamber to open? Clichéd. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Also, the concept of Mustafa’s library – a treasury of useless books in the desert, counterbalanced by photos of the ‘conquered’ British women, seems to me a romanticized symbol of colonization/ counter-colonization through education, reshaping/ owning ideas received from colonizers, and sex. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. <br /><br />Regarding the books’ representation of women: I am not revolted by it, merely unsatisfied. Hosna, Mustafa’s widow <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[(despite violent protestations of Arab scholars, I believe Mustafa simply upped and left, becoming responsible for yet another woman’s death. More precisely, he shares the responsibility with the narrator, who refuses to marry Hosna, who probably sees what’s coming and knows Wad Raees wants to add her to his collection of wives. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> resists remarriage, and later consummation of marriage with Wad Raees – yet somehow this seems less of a protest of a 20th century woman to how she’s treated by an oppressive society, nor does it feel entirely realistic; it becomes a myth. Hosna’s story makes me think of Arthurian legends. I see her fate as being killed by her environment, and then symbolically killed once more.<br /><br />Another thing I don’t fully understand is the biased representation of British women. The main message, to me, is that in the 1930s, a white woman would have to be seriously unstable (Ann), dying (Isabella), or politically involved (Sheila) to have sex with a dark-skinned man, and insane (Jean) to marry one. (The book’s representation of ‘filthy liberalism’ and where it can lead is interesting – not just today, when Donald Trump becomes the 45th president of the U.S.)<br /><br />Regarding the, erm, tangle of interrelated tragic events at the end of the novel (references under spoiler one), I can see a parallel between Mustafa’s British marriage (obsession, resistance, withholding sex, the event that shall not be named) and the marriage between Wad Raees and Hosna (pursuit, resistance, withholding sex, the event that shall not be named x 2). <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Hosna’s killing of Wad Raees seems to mirror Mustafa’s killing of Jane (interestingly, in both cases we see for ourselves, or hear from another character, that the dead were ‘asking for it’, albeit in different ways). All of the three murders are strongly sexualized – meaning not only the context, but also the symbolic charge (female genital mutilation in reverse, for instance). <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="13052944344141927741" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


